        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>You're about to head out for a Hudson Valley hike. You know you need protection against ticks and mosquitoes. You reach for bug spray. But which one?</p>
        <p>The bug repellent aisle is confusing. DEET, Picaridin, oil of lemon eucalyptus, "natural" sprays‚Äîwhich actually works? And which is safest for your family?</p>
        <p>The good news: the CDC has clear recommendations. For tick prevention specifically, Picaridin has emerged as an excellent option‚Äîsometimes even better than DEET.</p>

        <h2>How Bug Repellents Work</h2>
        <p>Bug repellents don't kill insects like permethrin does. Instead, they make it harder for insects to find you. They mask your carbon dioxide signature or irritate the insect's sensory organs, causing it to fly or crawl away.</p>
        <p>Different repellent chemicals work differently, which is why effectiveness varies.</p>

        <h2>DEET: The Gold Standard (Sort Of)</h2>

        <h3>What DEET Does</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Effective against mosquitoes, ticks, flies, chiggers, and other insects</li>
            <li>Protection duration: 4-6 hours (depending on concentration)</li>
            <li>Higher concentrations (30-40%) provide longer protection</li>
            <li>Works in most climates</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>DEET Pros</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Extensively tested over 50+ years</li>
            <li>Very effective against many insects</li>
            <li>Works at lower concentrations</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>DEET Cons</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Can damage certain plastics and synthetic fabrics</li>
            <li>Greasy feel on skin</li>
            <li>Can cause skin irritation in sensitive people</li>
            <li>Some people report a chemical odor</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Picaridin: The Rising Star</h2>

        <h3>What Picaridin Does</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Repels mosquitoes, ticks, flies, and other insects</li>
            <li>Similar effectiveness to DEET at comparable concentrations</li>
            <li>Protection duration: 8+ hours (longer than DEET)</li>
            <li>20% Picaridin = 200 times more effective than oil of lemon eucalyptus</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Picaridin Pros</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Lighter, non-greasy feel</li>
            <li>Doesn't damage plastics or synthetics</li>
            <li>Longer protection duration than DEET</li>
            <li>Less likely to cause skin irritation</li>
            <li>No harsh chemical smell</li>
            <li>Works great in humid climates</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Picaridin Cons</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Slightly less well-known than DEET</li>
            <li>Can be harder to find in some areas</li>
            <li>Slightly higher cost than some DEET products</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="pro-tip">
            <strong>üí° Pro Tip:</strong> For Hudson Valley residents, Picaridin is often the better choice because it lasts longer (especially important during all-day outdoor activities) and has a better feel on skin for frequent reapplication.
        </div>

