        <h2>How to Apply Repellent Correctly</h2>

        <ol>
            <li>Apply to exposed skin (arms, legs, neck)</li>
            <li>Apply to top of shoes and pant legs (ticks crawl up)</li>
            <li>Don't apply under clothing where ticks can hide</li>
            <li>Reapply after swimming or excessive sweating</li>
            <li>Use permethrin-treated clothing + Picaridin for best results</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="common-mistake">
            <strong>‚ö†Ô∏è Common Mistake:</strong> Using bug spray alone without treating clothing. Bug spray doesn't kill ticks; it repels them. Ticks can still climb through untreated fabrics. Always combine repellent with permethrin-treated clothing.
        </div>

        <h2>For Children and Pregnant Women</h2>

        <h3>Children 2 Months and Older</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Picaridin 10% is safe for children 2+ months</li>
            <li>DEET 10% is also safe for children 2+ months</li>
            <li>Never use on hands (they put hands in mouth)</li>
            <li>Apply to parent's hands, then rub on child</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Infants Under 2 Months</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Avoid repellents if possible</li>
            <li>Use protective clothing instead</li>
            <li>Keep them indoors during peak tick season if in high-risk areas</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Natural Alternatives (Reality Check)</h2>

        <p>Oil of lemon eucalyptus (OLE), citronella, and other "natural" options are less effective. Oil of lemon eucalyptus has some effectiveness but requires more frequent reapplication.</p>

        <div class="pro-tip">
            <strong>üí° Pro Tip:</strong> "Natural" doesn't mean safer or better. The CDC recommends DEET and Picaridin because they're well-studied and effective‚Äînot because they're chemicals. Picaridin is actually derived from a natural compound found in pepper plants.
        </div>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>For Hudson Valley tick prevention, Picaridin 20% offers excellent protection, lasts longer than DEET, and feels better on skin. Combined with permethrin-treated clothing and regular tick checks, it's a solid part of your defense strategy.</p>

        <p>Choose Picaridin for all-day outdoor activities. You'll appreciate the longer protection window and the light, non-greasy feel.</p>
